====================<http://www.dierkx-besson.eu/3D%20kukulkan.htm>====================
<html>
<head>
<META name="description" content="3D Kukulcan">
<META name="keywords" content="Erik Dierkx, Kukulcan, Kukulkan, Quetzalcoatl, Yucatan, Equinox, Ruins, Maya, Toltec, Pyramid, 3D, Galleries, Gallery, Model, Download, DXF, DWG, El Castillo, wallpaper, Animation, Autocad, Movie, Render, Mexico, Chichen Itza">
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<title>Erik &amp; Myriam's Homepage</title>
<link rel="shortcut icon" href="/favicon.ico">

</head>

<body background="kukulkan6a.jpg" bgproperties="fixed">

<center>

<table border="0" width="896" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" height="136">
  <tr>
    <td height="29">
<p><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2"><a href="index.html"><font color="#000000">Home</font></a></font></span>
    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td height="107">

<p class="MsoBodyText" align="center"><b><font face="Arial" color="#CC0000" size="5">3D
Kukulcn</font></b></p>
<p class="MsoBodyText" align="center"><b><font face="Arial" color="#CC0000" size="3">Gallery
with rendered threedimensional images of the Kukulcn pyramid, Chichn Itz,
Mexico</font></b></p>
      <p align="center">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<table border="0" width="896" height="171" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td width="170" height="165" background="k0.jpg" rowspan="11">&nbsp;</td>
    <td width="17" height="165" rowspan="11"></td>
    <td width="703" height="28" colspan="3">
<p class="MsoBodyText"><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2">On this
page you will find rendered images of the Kukulcn pyramid (also known as El
Castillo) in Chichn Itz,
Mexico. This is how I got the idea to make these images: When we visited the famous Maya pyramid in
2002 (click <a href="onze_huwelijksreis_naar_mexico.htm" target="_blank"> here</a> to read about our journey) we learned about
a mythic event, and amazing
spectacle, that takes place twice a year.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2">In brief: during the springtime and autumn equinox, the shadow of one side of the
Kukulcn pyramid
is cast in such a way on one of the central stairs that the shape of a snake
can be recognised. This snake figure was conceived to be a representation of the
Maya god Kukulcn, who seems to descend the stairs.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2">Since we
were not at the ruins during the equinox, we did not witness this ingenious display of
the Mayas' architectonic knowledge. Still, I wanted to see for myself how exactly
the snake figure is formed. So I used <a href="http://www.autodesk.com" target="_blank"> AutoCAD</a> to create a
three-dimensional model of
the pyramid. I found the dimensions on the internet (I would say that the model
is accurate for about 90%) and the many touristic pictures, available on the
internet, helped me a lot as well. Afterwards, I rendered the model,
introducing the geographic location of Chichn Itz</font></span><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2">
and the date and time of the equinox. The
program then calculates the position of the sun and so the shadows are
consistent with reality.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-GB"><font face="Arial" size="2"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rendering_(computer_graphics)" target="_blank">What
is rendering?</a></font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="703" height="5" colspan="3">
<hr>
    </center>

<center>

<p class="MsoNormal" align="center"><span lang="EN-GB" style="color:black"><font face="Arial" size="2"><span style="color: black"><b>Pictures
'taken' during the Equinox (click on picture to enlarge)</b></span></font></span></p>
